issue.title: Access clients of user-defined resources via simulator API
issue.body:
### Feature Spec

Today, the [simulator API](https://www.winglang.io/docs/concepts/simulator) only allows you to access a client for a resource if the resource's class was implemented in the SDK:

```js
import { testing } from '@winglang/sdk';

const sim = new testing.Simulator({ simfile: "hello.wsim" });
const fn = sim.getResource("root/Default/cloud.Function");
const response = await fn.invoke("hello!");

```

If you try calling `getResource` with a resource path corresponding to a class written in Wing, the simulator API throws an error.

We would like to lift this restriction so that clients of all resources in the app can be accessed.

### Use Cases

For Wing Console features

### Implementation Notes

_No response_

### Component

Compiler, SDK

### Community Notes

<!-- Please keep this note for the community -->
* Please vote by adding a 👍 reaction to the issue to help us prioritize.
* If you are interested to work on this issue, please leave a comment.
* If this issue is labeled **needs-discussion**, it means the spec has not been finalized yet. Please reach out on the #dev channel in the [Wing Slack](https://t.winglang.io/slack).

comment.body:
I am wondering if the culprit is that the Console is calling inflight APIs directly instead of a network interface.

Considering that soon enough we will need the Console to be able to interact with production Wing applications deployed to the cloud, the Console service won't even have permissions to execute inflight client code (eg call s3.PutObject).

I am wondering if the direction should be to use the simulator remoting API that we just introduced, and then we can evolve it to support production as well.

fix(compiler): can't inherit an stdlib resource (#4640)

Fixes #3585

Before this PR our dependency injection only worked on `new` calls. So when instantiating an stdlib `cloud.Api` for example you'd get a `cloud.Api` instance matching the desired target. But when inheriting from an stdlib preflight class dependency injection wasn't being done. So we just inherited the abstract base class. 
With this change we get dependency injection also when doing `extends cloud.SomeThing`. The way I got this to work is by changing the dep-injection mechanism to return not a concrete instance but rather a concrete type. Then we can instantiate that type or inherit it based on what we need.

fix(compiler): jsii import use-before-defined error (#4657)

Fixes #4575

This was a tricky bug to pin down. I initially thought it might be an issue with our symbol lookup code, but it turns out it was working fine - it instead there was an issue in our symbol environment construction. In `class2.w`, the `util` symbol had the was being stored with the span and statement index information associated with `class1.w`.

The root cause of this seems to be that after the first `bring util` statement, some of the import information is stored in `JsiiImportSpec`, which then got reused when `bring util` was called a second time. To fix this, I updated the logic we perform for bring-jsii statements so that it only reuses an existing `JsiiImportSpec` if the `alias` it has stored is exactly the same (both the string and its position in the source code).

I'm not sure if storing a separate `JsiiImportSpec` for every unique bring statement has any performance drawbacks but I didn't have enough context to easily refactor the `alias` and `import_statement_idx` fields out of `JsiiImportSpec`:

https://github.com/winglang/wing/blob/392aa4bdce6868ad01ac5df674a7decb0a823f21/libs/wingc/src/type_check/jsii_importer.rs#L51-L69

Definitely interested if there are ways to simplify this though.

This PR updates the file to include metadata about each resource's type, such as the simulation's source code location. This eliminates an ugly factory class that we've had to update each time someone adds a new resource to the simulator. 🙌

Since the Wing Console and SDK are happily living together in our monorepo and packaged together as part of the CLI, I've also cleaned up some cross-library type information so there's just one fully-qualified name constant associated with each SDK resource instead of two (see libs/wingsdk/src/target-sim/schema-resources.ts for the removal).
